{#- DEFINITION — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-help-reconciliation-broken-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">&ldquo;Reconciliation won&rsquo;t balance,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Reconciling is the monthly check that confirms your QuickBooks records match what the bank actually did: you mark each transaction that cleared, and at the end the difference between your cleared balance and the statement&rsquo;s ending balance should be <em>zero</em>. When people say reconciliation &ldquo;won&rsquo;t balance,&rdquo; they usually mean one of a few things: the difference at the end won&rsquo;t go to zero no matter what they check; the <em>beginning</em> balance QuickBooks shows doesn&rsquo;t match last period&rsquo;s ending balance; or a period they already reconciled has <em>changed</em> &mdash; an old reconciliation that used to tie suddenly doesn&rsquo;t.</p>
      <p>The good news is that most of these trace to a short list of causes, and the self-fix steps below address them in order of likelihood &mdash; running the Reconciliation Discrepancy Report and the Audit Log surfaces a large share of cases, because the usual culprit is a reconciled transaction someone edited, deleted, or voided after the fact. What the steps <em>can&rsquo;t</em> fix is a discrepancy that has compounded across many months, or a prior period that was &ldquo;balanced&rdquo; with a bogus adjustment to make the number go to zero. That part is a ProAdvisor job, not a single correction. And if the underlying issue is your Intuit account or login, that&rsquo;s Intuit&rsquo;s to resolve &mdash; not something we can reach.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

